answer:   As an ENFP, I would rate the statement "You think the world would be a better place if people relied more on rationality and less on their feelings" as a 1, strongly disagree. I enjoy exploring new possibilities and experiencing life to the fullest, and I find that planning too far in advance can stifle my creativity and enthusiasm. I am more likely to take things as they come and adapt to changing circumstances, rather than sticking to a rigid routine.

So while I can appreciate the value of having a backup plan, I tend to be more focused on exploring new possibilities and embracing the unknown rather than over-planning for every eventuality.'}]
answer:   As an ENFP person, I would rate the extent of my agreement with the statement "You often make a backup plan for a backup plan" as a 5. While I appreciate the importance of being prepared and having contingency plans in place, I tend to be more focused on the present moment and future possibilities than on creating elaborate backup plans for backup plans. I prefer to be flexible and adaptable, and I often find it difficult to predict what might happen in the future. While I can appreciate the value of philosophical inquiry and intellectual exploration, I tend to be more interested in exploring the world around me and engaging with others in a practical and spontaneous way.

7 - Strongly Disagree

I believe that everyone has their own strengths and weaknesses, and it's important to appreciate and respect people's differences rather than trying to impose my own efficiency standards on them. I enjoy collaborating with others and finding creative solutions to problems, and I believe that this approach often leads to more innovative and effective results than trying to force everyone to conform to a single, narrow standard.
